ted as the temperature drops. It has a NEMA Type 4 ingress rating against dust and rain, making it suitable for indoor or outdoor use. Anker says the Solix X1 operates at 35dB (which is slightly louder than a home theater projector) in temps below 104F (40C)."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"3EIccU","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"The Solix X1 requires professional installation and can be integrated with solar panels to create your own micro-grid after purchasing enough modules. Or you can use it to collect energy during the day and then feed it back into the home at night to lower energy bills. It also supports California’s Net Energy Metering 3.0 (NEM 3.0) policy so X1 owners can sell electricity back to the grid at peak hours."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false},{"__typename":"EntryBodyParagraph","placement":{"id":"DTtJpG","alignment":null},"__isEntryBodyComponent":"EntryBodyParagraph","contents":{"html":"Anker isn’t publishing prices, but you can \u003ca href=\"https://go.skimresources.com/?id=1025X1701640\u0026xs=1\u0026url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.anker.com%2Fanker-solix%2Fx1-energy-storage-system-hes\"\u003econtact Anker’s sales team\u003c/a\u003e for details if you’re interested in buying."},"dropcap":false,"endmark":false,"lead":false}]},"liveCoverageStart":null,"slug":"24136932/anker-solix-x1-home-battery-powerwall-alternative-specs","layoutTemplate":"STANDARD","seoSchema":[{"@context":"http://schema.org/","@type":"NewsArticle","headline":"Anker’s minimalistic home backup batteries are ready for blackout season","description":"The thin and minimalistic Solix X1 is a Tesla Powerwall alternative that can provide emergency power to a few appliances or the entire home.","datePublished":"2024-04-23T14:00:00.000Z","dateModified":"2024-04-23T14:00:00.000Z","thumbnailUrl":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/kCvj9n-tpWkJI8ohfrKm_rMjKP0=/0x0:6000x3614/1400x788/filters:focal(3000x1807:3001x1808)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411876/X1_Lifestyle01.jpg","author":[{"@type":"Person","name":"Thomas Ricker","url":"https://www.theverge.com/authors/thomas-ricker"}],"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"The Verge","logo":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/24015294/verge_duet_google_news.png","width":250,"height":50}},"image":[{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/kCvj9n-tpWkJI8ohfrKm_rMjKP0=/0x0:6000x3614/1400x788/filters:focal(3000x1807:3001x1808)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411876/X1_Lifestyle01.jpg","width":1400,"height":788},{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/AR3pAVn0PaYIYDLblfOCv1mo8sw=/0x0:6000x3614/1400x1050/filters:focal(3000x1807:3001x1808)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411876/X1_Lifestyle01.jpg","width":1400,"height":1050},{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/nuVoDy2LZEFBx7KY20OzHQHibto=/0x0:6000x3614/1400x1400/filters:focal(3000x1807:3001x1808)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411876/X1_Lifestyle01.jpg","width":1400,"height":1400}],"url":"https://www.theverge.com/24136932/anker-solix-x1-home-battery-powerwall-alternative-specs","articleBody":"Nearly a year since it was first announced, Anker is finally selling its Solix whole-home battery backup solution in North America. The Solix X1 is just 5.9 inches thick and attaches to a wall like a Tesla Powerwall. It’s a more permanent and minimalist alternative to Anker’s modular F3800 kits, which can be quickly detached to power a weekend away. \n\nThe Solix X1 can be configured to deliver between 3kW and 36kW of power with a stackable design that supports between 5kWh and 180kWh of LFP battery capacity. It’s covered by a warranty of 10 years or 16.5MWh throughput, whichever comes first. Cutover from the grid to the battery happens in less than 20ms, so you might not even notice the next power outage. \n\nCalculating how much power and capacity you need can be tricky, but fortunately, you can expand the Solix X1 over time as your needs and budget allow. According to the US Energy Information Administration, the average US home consumed 889kWh per month in 2022, or about 29.2kWh per day. But your battery system can be configured with much less capacity if you’re only interested in powering critical devices like the fridge, freezer, sump pump, and a few lights during blackouts, which are happening more frequently due to the rise in extreme weather.\n\n[Image: Rain. https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/2IsEpmkTQSrtvr180-3H2rlJ9ZI=/0x0:6000x3840/6000x3840/filters:focal(3000x1920:3001x1921)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411903/Warranty_and_Weather_Protection.jpg]\n[Image: Snow. https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/lWyXvpBRDbGyfqZyx35dCpPoQLs=/0x0:6000x3840/6000x3840/filters:focal(3000x1920:3001x1921)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411901/_4_C_131_C___Snow.jpg]\n[Image: Have our energy savings offset what we paid yet? https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/HScg33y0XNgL2JP1HH0jQk_qdfk=/0x0:8192x5464/8192x5464/filters:focal(4096x2732:4097x2733)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411898/Bill_Saving.jpg]\n[Image: Living the EV micro-grid life. https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/AyVDM6ccNQatyP3UCHV6EvHdjO4=/0x0:3915x2541/3915x2541/filters:focal(1958x1271:1959x1272)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411899/Charging_EV_2.jpg]\n[Image: Two professionals being too professional. https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/7YQoIChsp5iQZViIigFG38ak9Uw=/0x0:6720x4480/6720x4480/filters:focal(3360x2240:3361x2241)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411900/X1_Installation.jpg]\n[Image: It has an app. https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/Cbr6rPUtBvQxuuqlXst1RCf00ek=/0x0:8192x5464/8192x5464/filters:focal(4096x2732:4097x2733)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411902/One_App_to_Monitor_and_Optimize_Home_Power_Usage.jpg]\n\nLike other home backup systems, the Solix X1 will automatically charge itself if severe weather is forecasted. It’s also designed to operate normally in temperatures as high as 131 degrees Fahrenheit (55 degrees Celsius) or as low as -4F (-20C) thanks to batteries that are automatically heated as the temperature drops. It has a NEMA Type 4 ingress rating against dust and rain, making it suitable for indoor or outdoor use. Anker says the Solix X1 operates at 35dB (which is slightly louder than a home theater projector) in temps below 104F (40C).\n\nThe Solix X1 requires professional installation and can be integrated with solar panels to create your own micro-grid after purchasing enough modules. Or you can use it to collect energy during the day and then feed it back into the home at night to lower energy bills. It also supports California’s Net Energy Metering 3.0 (NEM 3.0) policy so X1 owners can sell electricity back to the grid at peak hours.\n\nAnker isn’t publishing prices, but you can contact Anker’s sales team for details if you’re interested in buying.\n"}],"package":null,"url":"https://www.theverge.com/24136932/anker-solix-x1-home-battery-powerwall-alternative-specs","commentsClosed":false,"railComponents":[{"__typename":"EntryRailNewsletter","entryRailNewsletter":{"name":"Verge Deals","slug":"deals"}}],"dek":{"plaintext":"The Solix X1 can be configured to power a few appliances or take the entire home off the grid."},"leadImage":{"defaultImageUrl":"https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/3GaRSWnDzHCnDwLQgMdNrZOg2yo=/0x0:6000x3614/1200x628/filters:focal(3000x1807:3001x1808)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25411876/X1_Lifestyle01.jpg","asset":{"title":null,"contentType":"image/jpeg"}},"seoDescription":{"plaintext":"The thin and minimalistic Solix X1 is a Tesla Powerwall alternative that can provide emergency power to a few appliances or the entire home."},"socialDescription":{"plaintext":"Energy independence for anyone that can afford it."},"socialImage":null,"shouldUseHTMLN